<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-04-03T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-04-03T13:00:00-05:00" n="229" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d229">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">862.4016/362: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy (<persName type="from">Garrett</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-04-03T19:00:00+01:00">April
                                        3, 1933—7 p.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received April 3—2:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>21. The British Ambassador tells me that in a talk this afternoon
                                with the Chief of the Government, Mussolini told him that he was
                                continuing to make the strongest possible representations at Berlin
                                against the anti-Jewish action of the Hitler Government and that he,
                                Mussolini, believed this agitation would shortly cease.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Garrett</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>